SIMPLE: in
RECORDS: 7

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: In-
<hw>In-</hw> <pr>(⟦icr⟧n-)</pr>. <ety>[See <er>In</er>, <pos>prep.</pos>
Cf. <er>Em-</er>, <er>En-</er>.]</ety> <def>A prefix from Eng. prep.
<xex>in</xex>, also from Lat. prep. <xex>in</xex>, meaning
<sig>in</sig>, <sig>into</sig>, <sig>on</sig>, <sig>among</sig>; <as>as,
<ex>in</ex>bred, <ex>in</ex>born, <ex>in</ex>road; <xex>in</xex>cline,
<xex>in</xex>ject, <xex>in</xex>trude</as>. In words from the Latin,
<xex>in-</xex> regularly becomes <xex>il-</xex> before <xex>l</xex>,
<xex>ir-</xex> before <xex>r</xex>, and <xex>im-</xex> before a labial;
<as>as, <ex>il</ex>lusion, <ex>ir</ex>ruption, <ex>im</ex>blue,
<ex>im</ex>migrate, <ex>im</ex>part</as>. <xex>In-</xex> is sometimes
used with an simple intensive force.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>In-</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: In-
<hw>In-</hw> <pr>(⟦icr⟧n-)</pr>. <ety>[L. <ets>in</ets>-; akin to E.
<ets>un</ets>-. See <er>Un-</er>.]</ety> <def>An inseparable prefix, or
particle, meaning <sig>not</sig>, <sig>non</sig>-, <sig>un-</sig> as,
<xex>in</xex>active, <xex>in</xex>capable, <xex>in</xex>apt.
<xex>In-</xex> regularly becomes <xex>il-</xex> before <xex>l</xex>,
<xex>ir-</xex> before <xex>r</xex>, and <xex>im-</xex> before a
labial.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>-in</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: -in
<hw>-in</hw>. <def>A suffix. See the Note under <er>-ine</er>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>In</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: In
<hw>In</hw>, <pos>prep.</pos> <ety>[AS. <ets>in</ets>; akin to D. & G.
<ets>in</ets>, Icel. <ets>⟦imac⟧</ets>, Sw. & Dan. <ets>i</ets>, OIr. &
L. <ets>in</ets>, Gr. <grk>'en</grk>. ⟦root⟧197. Cf. 1st <er>In-</er>,
<er>Inn</er>.]</ety> <def>The specific signification of <xex>in</xex> is
situation or place with respect to surrounding, environment,
encompassment, etc. It is used with verbs signifying being, resting, or
moving within limits, or within circumstances or conditions of any kind
conceived of as limiting, confining, or investing, either wholly or in
part. In its different applications, it approaches some of the meanings
of, and sometimes is interchangeable with, <xex>within</xex>,
<xex>into</xex>, <xex>on</xex>, <xex>at</xex>, <xex>of</xex>, and
<xex>among</xex>.</def> It is used: --⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>With reference to space or place; <as>as, he lives
<ex>in</ex> Boston; he traveled <ex>in</ex> Italy; castles <ex>in</ex>
the air.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The babe lying <qex>in</qex> a manger.</q> <rj><qau>Luke ii.
16.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Thy sun sets weeping <qex>in</qex> the lowly west.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Situated <qex>in</qex> the forty-first degree of latitude.</q>
<rj><qau>Gibbon.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Matter for censure <qex>in</qex> every page.</q>
<rj><qau>Macaulay.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>With reference to circumstances or conditions;
<as>as, he is <ex>in</ex> difficulties; she stood <ex>in</ex> a blaze of
light.</as></def> ⟦ldquo⟧Fettered <xex>in</xex> amorous chains.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Wrapt <qex>in</qex> sweet sounds, as <qex>in</qex> bright
veils.</q> <rj><qau>Shelley.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>With reference to a whole which includes or
comprises the part spoken of; <as>as, the first <ex>in</ex> his family;
the first regiment <ex>in</ex> the army.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Nine <qex>in</qex> ten of those who enter the ministry.</q>
<rj><qau>Swift.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>With reference to physical surrounding, personal
states, etc., abstractly denoted; <as>as, I am <ex>in</ex> doubt; the
room is <ex>in</ex> darkness; to live <ex>in</ex> fear.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>When shall we three meet again,⟦br⟧
<qex>In</qex> thunder, lightning, or <qex>in</qex> rain?</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>With reference to character, reach, scope, or
influence considered as establishing a limitation; <as>as, to be
<ex>in</ex> one's favor</as>.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧<xex>In</xex> sight of God's
high throne.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Milton.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Sounds inharmonious <qex>in</qex> themselves, and harsh.</q>
<rj><qau>Cowper.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>With reference to movement or tendency toward a
certain limit or environment; -- sometimes equivalent to
<xex>into</xex>; <as>as, to put seed <ex>in</ex> the ground; to fall
<ex>in</ex> love; to end <ex>in</ex> death; to put our trust <ex>in</ex>
God.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He would not plunge his brother <qex>in</qex> despair.</q>
<rj><qau>Addison.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>She had no jewels to deposit <qex>in</qex> their caskets.</q>
<rj><qau>Fielding.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <def>With reference to a limit of time; <as>as,
<ex>in</ex> an hour; it happened <ex>in</ex> the last century;
<ex>in</ex> all my life.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><mcol><col><b>In as much as</b></col>, <it>or</it>
<col><b>Inasmuch as</b></col></mcol>, <cd>in the degree that; in like
manner as; in consideration that; because that; since. See
<er>Synonym</er> of <er>Because</er>, and cf. <cref>For as much
as</cref>, under <er>For</er>, <pos>prep.</pos></cd> -- <col><b>In
that</b></col>, <cd>because; for the reason that.</cd> ⟦ldquo⟧Some
things they do <xex>in that</xex> they are men . . . ; some things
<xex>in that</xex> they are men misled and blinded with error.⟦rdquo⟧
<au>Hooker.</au> -- <col><b>In the name of</b></col>, <cd>in behalf of;
on the part of; by authority; as, it was done <xex>in the name of</xex>
the people; -- often used in invocation, swearing, praying, and the
like.</cd> -- <col><b>To be in for it</b></col>. <sd>(a)</sd> <cd>To be
in favor of a thing; to be committed to a course.</cd> <sd>(b)</sd>
<cd>To be unable to escape from a danger, penalty, etc.</cd>
<mark>[Colloq.]</mark> -- <mcol><col><b>To be in with</b></col>
<it>or</it> <col><b>To keep in with</b></col></mcol>. <sd>(a)</sd>
<cd>To be close or near; <as>as, to <ex>keep</ex> a ship <ex>in
with</ex> the land</as>.</cd> <sd>(b)</sd> <cd>To be on terms of
friendship, familiarity, or intimacy with; to secure and retain the
favor of.</cd> <mark>[Colloq.]</mark></cs></p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Into; within; on; at. See <er>At</er>.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>In</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 5 ====
HEADWORD: In
<hw>In</hw>, <pos>adv.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Not out; within; inside.
<xex>In</xex>, the preposition, becomes an adverb by omission of its
object, leaving it as the representative of an adverbial phrase, the
context indicating what the omitted object is; <as>as, he takes
<ex>in</ex> the situation (<it>i. e.</it>, he comprehends it
<xex>in</xex> his mind); the Republicans were <xex>in</xex> (<it>i.
e.</it>, <xex>in</xex> office); <xex>in</xex> at one ear and out at the
other (<it>i. e.</it>, <xex>in</xex> or <xex>into</xex> the head); his
side was <xex>in</xex> (<it>i. e.</it>, <xex>in</xex> the turn at the
bat); he came <xex>in</xex> (<it>i. e.</it>, into the
house)</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Their vacation . . . falls <qex>in</qex> so pat with ours.</q>
<rj><qau>Lamb.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<note><p>⟦hand⟧ The sails of a vessel are said, in nautical language, to
be <xex>in</xex> when they are furled, or when stowed.</p>

<p> In certain cases <xex>in</xex> has an adjectival sense; as, the
<xex>in</xex> train (<it>i. e.</it>, the incoming train); compare
<xex>up</xex> grade, <xex>down</xex> grade, <xex>under</xex>tow,
<xex>after</xex>thought, etc.⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p></note>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Law)</fld> <def>With privilege or possession; --
used to denote a holding, possession, or seizin; <as>as, <ex>in</ex> by
descent; <ex>in</ex> by purchase; <ex>in</ex> of the seisin of her
husband.</as></def> <rj><au>Burrill.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>In and in breeding</b></col>. <cd>See under
<er>Breeding</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>In and out</b></col>
<fld>(Naut.)</fld>, <cd>through and through; -- said of a through bolt
in a ship's side.</cd> <au>Knight.</au> -- <col><b>To be in</b></col>,
<cd>to be at home; <as>as, Mrs. A. <ex>is in</ex></as>.</cd> --
<col><b>To come in</b></col>. <cd>See under <er>Come</er>.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>In</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 6 ====
HEADWORD: In
<hw>In</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <note>[Usually in the plural.]</note>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>One who is in office; -- the opposite of
<ant>out</ant>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A re⟦eum⟧ntrant angle; a nook or corner.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Ins and outs</b></col>, <sd>(a)</sd> <cd>nooks and
corners; twists and turns.</cd> <sd>(b)</sd> <cd>the peculiarities or
technicalities (of a subject); intricacies; details; -- used with
<ptcl>of</ptcl>; <as>as, he knew the <ex>ins and outs</ex> of the
Washington power scene</as>.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><q>All the <qex>ins and outs</qex> of this neighborhood.</q>
<rj><qau>D. Jerrold.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- p. 741 --></p>

<p><ent>In</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 7 ====
HEADWORD: In
<hw>In</hw> <pr>(⟦icr⟧n)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To inclose; to take
in; to harvest.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He that ears my land spares my team and gives me leave to
<qex>in</qex> the crop.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Inability</ent>⟦br⟧
